 First, we calculate the daily revenue from selling eggs \text{Daily revenue} = \text{Number of eggs sold} \times \text{Price per egg} 
 \text{Daily revenue} = 252 \text{ eggs/day} \times \$2/\text{dozen} 
 \text{Daily revenue} = \$504/\text{day} 
Since Lloyd sells eggs weekly, we need to find the weekly revenue \text{Weekly revenue} = \text{Daily revenue} \times 7 \text{ days} 
 \text{Weekly revenue} = \$504/\text{day} \times 7 \text{ days} 
 \text{Weekly revenue} = \$3,636/\text{week} 
Therefore, Lloyd makes $3,636 per week from selling eggs.
The answer is: $3,636

 First, we need to find the total time it takes for Tom to travel from 1 to 4 PM.  Since he travels at 10 mph, we use the formula
 \text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Speed}} 

Given that the distance is 4 - 1 = 3 miles, and his speed is 10 miles per hour, we substitute these values into the formula
 \text{Time} = \frac{3}{10} \text{ hours} 

 \text{Time} = 0.3 \text{ hours} 

Since we want to find the time it takes to get back from 4 to 1 PM, we subtract the time it took to get from 1 to 4 PM from the total time
 \text{Time to get back} = 0.3 \text{ hours} - \frac{1}{10} \text{ hours} 

 \text{Time to get back} = 0.3 \text{ hours} - 0.1 \text{ hours} 

 \text{Time to get back} = 0.2 \text{ hours} 

Therefore, it takes Tom 0.2 hours, or 12 minutes, to get back from 4 to 1 PM.

The answer is: 0.2 hours

