 First, we need to find out how far James has swum. Since he swims 60% of the distance, we calculate 60% of 20 miles as follows \text{Distance swum} = 60\% \times 20 \text{ miles} 
 \text{Distance swum} = 0.6 \times 20 \text{ miles} 
 \text{Distance swum} = 12 \text{ miles} 
Since James swims at 2 miles per hour, we calculate the time taken to swim 12 miles as follows \text{Time taken} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Speed}} 
 \text{Time taken} = \frac{12 \text{ miles}}{2 \text{ miles/hour}} 
 \text{Time taken} = 6 \text{ hours} 
However, since James stops on an island and rests for half of the swimming time, we need to calculate the actual time taken to swim 12 miles. Since he stops, we consider the time spent resting as half of the swimming time. Therefore, the time taken to swim 12 miles is \text{Time taken} = \frac{1}{2} \times 6 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Time taken} = 3 \text{ hours} 
To find the total time taken to cross the lake, we add the time taken to swim 12 miles and the time spent resting \text{Total time} = 6 \text{ hours} + \frac{1}{2} \times 3 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Total time} = 6 \text{ hours} + 1.5 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Total time} = 7.5 \text{ hours} 
Therefore, it took James 7.5 hours to get across the lake.
The answer is: 7.5 hours

 First, we need to find out how many 15-minute intervals Vince was present. Since he was present from 8:00 AM to 11:00 PM, he was present for 3 hours and 0 minutes. We convert 0 minutes to hours because there are 60 minutes in an hour. Therefore, Vince was present for 3 hours and 0 minutes. Now, we multiply the number of hours by the number of minutes in an hour to get the total minutes Vince was present. 
